Plotting pie chart¶

In [38]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
data=pd.read_csv("D:\\Internship Progress\\WEEK3 new updated\\WEEK3\\Hospitality\\check-in - Copy.csv")
count_positive = 0
count_negative = 0
count_neutral = 0

for sentiment in data['sentiment']:
    if sentiment == 'Positive':
        count_positive += 1
    else:
        count_negative += 1
total=len(data)
positive_response= (count_positive / total) * 100
negative_response = (count_negative / total) * 100
myexplode = [0.2, 0]
y=[positive_response,negative_response]
plt.pie(y,labels=[str(round(positive_response,2))+"%",str(round(negative_response,2))+"%"],explode = myexplode, shadow = True,colors=["g","r"])
plt.title("Check IN tweet % distribution")
plt.legend(["positive","negative"])
plt.show()

LDA for positive tweets¶

In [1]:
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer
from sklearn.decomposition import LatentDirichletAllocation

from sklearn.feature_extraction import text

# Read the positive reviews data
positive_reviews = pd.read_csv("D:\\Internship Progress\\WEEK3 new updated\\WEEK3\\Hospitality\\check-in - Copy.csv")

# Combine reviews into a list
reviews = positive_reviews['tweet'].tolist()

# Create a custom stop words list if needed
custom_stop_words = ["read", "good", "disney", "yorker", "day", "didn", "stay", "great", "check", "booked", "like", "die", "told", "friendly", "clean", "sehr", "das", "zimmer", "und", "nice", "did", "was", "really", "safe", "walk", "close", "got"]

# Add your custom stop words to this list
stop_words = text.ENGLISH_STOP_WORDS.union(custom_stop_words)

# Vectorize the text data
vectorizer = CountVectorizer(max_df=0.95, min_df=2, stop_words=stop_words)
X = vectorizer.fit_transform(reviews)

# Apply LDA for topic modeling
num_topics = 5
lda = LatentDirichletAllocation(n_components=num_topics, random_state=42)
lda.fit(X)

# Extract top words for each topic
feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()
topics = []
for topic_idx, topic in enumerate(lda.components_):
    top_words_idx = topic.argsort()[-10:]
    top_words = [feature_names[i] for i in top_words_idx]
    topics.append(top_words)

# Print the top words for each topic (possible reasons for positive reviews)


for i, topic in enumerate(topics):
    print(f"Topic {i + 1}: {', '.join(topic)}")

Topic 1: lost, flight, boarding, request, time, support, digi, yatra, laptop, security
Topic 2: experience, helpful, minutes, staff, india, security, amp, gate, flight, boarding
Topic 3: extra, counter, number, 15, toll, went, inr, 1100, luggage, pay
Topic 4: mins, unable, digiyatra, based, experience, process, flight, hours, security, checkin
Topic 5: service, t2, checks, flight, checkin, blrairport, help, queue, digiyatra, security

Observation on positive tweet¶

  • ### Digi yatra is a popular and well-received service, with a 65.59% positive tweet sentiment.
  • ### Users appreciate the convenience, efficiency, and time-saving benefits of digi yatra.
  • ### Digi yatra is also helpful for resolving security issues and getting assistance from airport staff.
  • ### Some users reported minor issues such as extra baggage charges and the inability to use digi yatra in all cases.

  • ### However, the overall feedback is positive, and digi yatra is seen as a valuable addition to the airport experience. ## Recommendations:

  • ### Continue to invest in digi yatra infrastructure and support to ensure a smooth and seamless experience for all users.

  • ### Explore ways to reduce extra baggage charges and make digi yatra more accessible to all travelers. Work with airlines and airports to ensure that digi yatra is accepted and used at all stages of the travel journey.

Word Cloud for positive tweets¶

In [2]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from wordcloud import WordCloud

# Create a word cloud object
wc = WordCloud(background_color="white", max_font_size=50)

# Check the type of the topics variable
if isinstance(topics, list):
    # Convert the topics variable to a list of strings
    topics = [" ".join(topic) for topic in topics]

# Generate the word cloud
wc.generate(" ".join(topics))

# Plot the word cloud
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
plt.imshow(wc)
plt.axis("off")
plt.title("Top Words in Positive Reviews")
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer
from sklearn.decomposition import LatentDirichletAllocation

from sklearn.feature_extraction import text

# Read the negative reviews data
negative_reviews = pd.read_csv("D:\\Internship Progress\\WEEK3 new updated\\WEEK3\\Hospitality\\check-in.csv")

# Combine reviews into a list
reviews = negative_reviews['tweet'].tolist()

# Create a custom stop words list if needed
custom_stop_words = ["read", "good", "disney", "yorker", "day", "didn", "stay", "great", "check", "booked", "like", "die", "told", "friendly", "clean", "sehr", "das", "zimmer", "und", "nice", "did", "was", "really", "safe", "walk", "close", "got"]

# Add your custom stop words to this list
stop_words = text.ENGLISH_STOP_WORDS.union(custom_stop_words)

# Vectorize the text data
vectorizer = CountVectorizer(max_df=0.95, min_df=2, stop_words=stop_words)
X = vectorizer.fit_transform(reviews)

# Apply LDA for topic modeling
num_topics = 5
lda = LatentDirichletAllocation(n_components=num_topics, random_state=42)
lda.fit(X)

# Extract top words for each topic
feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()
topics = []
for topic_idx, topic in enumerate(lda.components_):
    top_words_idx = topic.argsort()[-10:]
    top_words = [feature_names[i] for i in top_words_idx]
    topics.append(top_words)

# Print the top words for each topic (possible reasons for positive reviews)


for i, topic in enumerate(topics):
    print(f"Topic {i + 1}: {', '.join(topic)}")

Topic 1: service, counter, left, bag, inside, sent, dont, stuck, disappointing, problem
Topic 2: management, baggage, counters, print, lost, security, counter, queue, indigo, flight
Topic 3: excess, worst, priority, staff, baggage, bag, left, stuck, passengers, counter
Topic 4: bag, akasa, boarding, baggage, luggage, akasaair, counter, experience, staff, checkin
Topic 5: open, unacceptable, making, counter, people, mumbai, staff, ticket, flight, amp

Observation on negative tweets¶

  • ### Negative experiences with baggage handling were commonly reported, including lost or delayed baggage, long queues at the counters, and rude or unhelpful staff.
  • ### Passengers also expressed dissatisfaction with the cost of excess baggage charges and the lack of priority handling for priority passengers.
  • ### Overall, the feedback suggests that there is room for improvement in the baggage handling process at all of the airlines and airports mentioned in the topics. ## Recommendations:
  • ### Airlines and airports should review their baggage handling procedures and staff training to ensure that all passengers have a smooth and efficient experience.
  • ### Airlines should be more transparent about baggage charges and priority handling policies.
  • ### Airlines and airports should work to reduce wait times at the counters by increasing staff and improving efficiency.
  • ### Staff should be more helpful and responsive to passenger concerns.
